      &lt;Value&gt;&lt;![CDATA[&lt;div class=&quot;exercise&quot; style=&#39;padding-left:0px;margin-left:0px;&#39;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;body&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;col-xs-12 nopadding&quot;&gt;
          &lt;h3&gt;Marketers&#39; Strengths:&lt;/h3&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;Marketers are masters of quick changes in a fast-paced environment. Beyond that, changes that require new outlooks or habits – especially among a group of people – can make the best of us feel like a fish out of water. Fortunately, &quot;change management&quot; thinking is a lot like planning a marketing campaign: who&#39;s affected, what&#39;s in it for them, how to get their attention, and how to build engagement.&lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;h3&gt;Scenario:&lt;/h3&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;Kelly is leading a task force to integrate communications across the company’s divisions for events, ads, media relations, and all other communications. Decentralized management has led to inconsistencies and duplication of resources. After the first meeting, Kelly realized that there are some strong opinions in the group, and it will be challenging to get everyone “on the same page.&lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;h3&gt;Approach:&lt;/h3&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;To manage others’ adoption of change:
          &lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;Identify the roles they need to play,&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;assess “what’s in it for me” from their perspective,&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;create a change playbook to guide your interactions with them, and&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;leverage early adopters of change to bring along the others.&lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;/ol&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
